    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1943-11-03T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1943-11-03T00:00:00-05:00" n="747"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d747">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">811.79682/65</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Liberia</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Walton</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 190</seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Monrovia</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1943-11-03">November 3,
                            1943</date>.<lb/>[Received November 16.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have the honor to refer to the Department’s
                    Airgram No. A–22, July 26, 1943, and to state that, in my opinion, there is
                    little or no likelihood of obtaining for Pan American Airways and its personnel
                    the exemptions in Article 4 of the Defense Agreement of March 31, 1942, between
                    the Government of the United States and the Government of Liberia, because: (1)
                    It is quite probable that the Government of Liberia would take the position that
                    such an amendment would become coterminous with the life of the Agreement
                    concluded between the Government of Liberia and Pan American Airways on July 14,
                    1941; (2) It would appear that the Liberian Government is inclined to believe
                    that Pan American Airways is carrying others than members of the armed forces
                    and civilians whose transportation has been approved as essential to the
                    prosecution of the war.</p>
                <p>It has occurred to me that probably a temporary arrangement might be effectuated
                    designed to obtain for the duration the desired exemptions for Pan American
                    Airways and individual members of the Pan American Airways staff.</p>
                <p>Respectfully yours,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Lester</hi> A. <hi rend="smallcaps">Walton</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
